48
00:06:14,500 --> 00:06:23,500
I personally would prefer the latter, to make a judgment on what to do with the bill today.

49
00:06:23,500 --> 00:06:39,000
But if there is an intense desire to study the bill, we could do that for a couple of weeks before we have to finish it and wrap up our recommendation.

50
00:06:39,000 --> 00:06:46,000
So I'd like to hear from the members about what their feelings might be.

51
00:06:46,000 --> 00:06:48,000
Representative Arrington.

52
00:06:48,000 --> 00:06:50,000
Yeah.

53
00:06:50,000 --> 00:06:56,000
I mean, let's just start with a little bit of history here.

54
00:06:56,000 --> 00:07:00,000
It's been, I don't know how many years.

55
00:07:00,000 --> 00:07:09,000
I think Al Gore made his famous speech about the end of the world coming in 10 years.

56
00:07:09,000 --> 00:07:15,000
That was about 16, 17 years ago, and the world hasn't ended.

57
00:07:15,000 --> 00:07:19,500
So everybody's been inundated with global warming, climate change.

58
00:07:19,500 --> 00:07:29,500
Nobody in New Hampshire, unless they're literally living underground someplace, is unaware of all the information available on climate change.

59
00:07:29,500 --> 00:07:45,500
Given that, I don't think beyond 2025, we should make the assumption that the people of New Hampshire are too ignorant to make a decision on what type of electricity to buy.

60
00:07:45,500 --> 00:07:55,000
They can buy whatever they want, and we should allow them the freedom to make that decision for themselves.

61
00:07:55,000 --> 00:08:17,500
A little more historical thing, people may or may not know, there's actually a law on the books that says utilities must provide up to 100% renewable energy if requested by a customer, and the customer has to pay any additional costs associated with that.

62
00:08:17,500 --> 00:08:19,500
That law was suspended.

63
00:08:19,500 --> 00:08:25,500
There was provision to suspend it if there was lack of participation.

64
00:08:25,500 --> 00:08:35,000
When the law was in effect, 0.2%, that 0.2% of people opted to pay extra to get renewable energy.

65
00:08:35,000 --> 00:08:45,500
Now, subsequent to that, there's been more available options for competitive suppliers, some of which provide all wind energy or whatever.

66
00:08:45,500 --> 00:08:55,500
So there's really no need for the state to say, you're not smart enough to make a decision for yourself.

67
00:08:55,500 --> 00:09:01,500
We're going to force you to buy the right type of electricity.

68
00:09:01,500 --> 00:09:05,000
This is simply a matter of freedom.

69
00:09:05,000 --> 00:09:08,000
No one out there is ignorant.

70
00:09:08,000 --> 00:09:19,500
No one can say, well, they don't know anything about the need for renewable energy because we constantly get bombarded with that information.

71
00:09:19,500 --> 00:09:21,500
It's everywhere you turn.

72
00:09:21,500 --> 00:09:36,000
So I think it's time to tell the people of New Hampshire, yes, we recognize you're intelligent enough to make a decision on what type of electricity to buy.

73
00:09:36,000 --> 00:09:49,500
Just like we say, we don't say, well, you have to buy a certain percentage of your produce must be organically grown because it's healthier for you.

74
00:09:49,500 --> 00:09:58,500
Or a certain percentage of the milk you buy must be skim milk because that's healthier for you.

75
00:09:58,500 --> 00:10:02,500
We let these people make their own decisions.

76
00:10:02,500 --> 00:10:06,500
They can do it with electricity as well.

77
00:10:06,500 --> 00:10:08,500
Okay.

78
00:10:08,500 --> 00:10:11,000
Question for you, Representative Harrington.

79
00:10:11,000 --> 00:10:17,000
Was the phase out of the original bill a five-year phase out?

80
00:10:17,000 --> 00:10:19,500
Is that what you recommended?

81
00:10:19,500 --> 00:10:57,500
Yeah, I believe it was because even though I don't think anybody that gets government subsidies has a right to those subsidies, but in trying to be a little bit fairer, it would be if you were getting the subsidies now, this phase out would allow you to make plans for the future so you could market yourself to people just the way other products do rather than lobbying at the state house for additional subsidies.

82
00:10:57,500 --> 00:11:02,000
So that was the purpose of the five-year phase-out.

83
00:11:02,000 --> 00:11:13,500
Was there any provision in the bill for grandfathering people who had installed renewable energy based on the provisions of the program earlier?

84
00:11:13,500 --> 00:11:15,500
No.

85
00:11:15,500 --> 00:11:38,000
Again, anybody that receives a subsidy from the government should not say, well, since you're giving me $20 for a subsidy, forcing to take it from the rate payers and giving it to me, you don't have a right to continue to get that forever.

86
00:11:38,000 --> 00:11:40,500
There was never any commitment.

87
00:11:40,500 --> 00:11:55,000
There was never anything in the bill that said, okay, if you put in renewable energy and you qualify for the RPS, we will pay you forever on it.

88
00:11:55,000 --> 00:11:57,000
That was never stated.

89
00:11:57,000 --> 00:12:03,000
In fact, the bill had a phase-out time, built with it, 2025.

90
00:12:03,000 --> 00:12:10,000
And I think that this is even a little bit more generous than that.

91
00:12:10,000 --> 00:12:18,000
But again, because you're getting a subsidy doesn't mean you have a right to the subsidy.

92
00:12:18,000 --> 00:12:21,500
That's a decision that can be made.

93
00:12:21,500 --> 00:12:27,000
It can be granted and be taken away by the state.

94
00:12:27,000 --> 00:12:36,500
And the bill did restore the requirement that the utilities offer 100% renewable resource-generated power if customers wanted that?

95
00:12:36,500 --> 00:12:40,000
Yes, I believe that was in there.

96
00:12:40,000 --> 00:12:46,000
It just basically, what happened was the utilities jointly petitioned the PUC.

97
00:12:46,000 --> 00:13:08,500
I was on the commission at the time, and they brought forward that the administrative costs of that particular program where people could request up to the 100% renewable energy, that was borne by the ratepayers, not by the people who selected the renewable energy.

98
00:13:08,500 --> 00:13:18,000
Any additional cost associated with the procurement of the renewable energy was borne by the person who requested it.

99
00:13:18,000 --> 00:13:26,000
But they came forward to us and said, look, 0.2% of the people are requesting this.

100
00:13:26,000 --> 00:13:34,500
The administrative costs are so high, and we can't justify them based on the small participation rate.

101
00:13:34,500 --> 00:13:41,000
And since the law allow the PUC to suspend it, it was suspended.

102
00:13:41,000 --> 00:13:43,000
Okay.

103
00:13:43,000 --> 00:13:45,000
Additional...

104
00:13:45,000 --> 00:13:48,500
them based on this small participation rate.

105
00:13:48,500 --> 00:13:55,000
And since the law allowed the PUC to suspend it, it was suspended.

106
00:13:55,000 --> 00:13:57,000
Okay.

107
00:13:57,000 --> 00:13:59,000
Additional comments about this.

108
00:13:59,000 --> 00:14:01,000
Representative McGee.

109
00:14:01,000 --> 00:14:03,000
Thank you, Mr.

110
00:14:03,000 --> 00:14:05,000
Chair.

111
00:14:05,000 --> 00:14:24,000
So my understanding is the renewable portfolio standards came into being as a way for the state to sort of keep track of how we were doing in terms of adoption of local sustainable, cleaner sources of energy.

112
00:14:24,000 --> 00:14:42,500
And that was in part because we had plans we were trying to make available to businesses and to individuals about how the state was addressing the need to lower our emissions and dependence on fossil fuels.

113
00:14:42,500 --> 00:14:57,500
So the Renewable Portfolio Standard, as it stands, as I think the chairman alluded to, the program provides price signals in the market for various categories of energy, including hydro.

114
00:14:57,500 --> 00:15:10,500
There are a number of impacts that would happen from this phase out to the economics of clean energy sources that we have in the state.

115
00:15:10,500 --> 00:15:36,500
And that's the reason that I would probably, on this bill, I would vote not to recommend that it go forward because I think there is a lot more of an analysis about what the impact is to people who have made plans around the fact that the state has an RPS.

116
00:15:36,500 --> 00:15:54,000
And I realize that additional legislation is likely to come because we have an end date on the existing RPS statute of 2025, with a goal of 25% of our energy being from renewable sources.

117
00:15:54,000 --> 00:15:59,000
So I think we do need to address this issue.

118
00:15:59,000 --> 00:16:19,500
But I think this concept of phasing it out without analyzing what that will do to the markets and what that will do to businesses and what that will do to people who are operating clean energy operations in New Hampshire.

119
00:16:19,500 --> 00:16:24,000
I don't think we want to disincentivize them either.

120
00:16:24,000 --> 00:16:37,000
So I don't feel there's been enough information on the economics of the effects of what would happen if we decided to phase the program out.

121
00:16:37,000 --> 00:16:39,500
So that's what I think.

122
00:16:39,500 --> 00:16:41,500
Okay.

123
00:16:41,500 --> 00:16:43,500
Additional comments.

124
00:16:43,500 --> 00:16:45,500
Representative Kaplan.

125
00:16:45,500 --> 00:16:49,500
Yeah, I just want to thank you, Mr.

126
00:16:49,500 --> 00:16:51,500
Chair.

127
00:16:51,500 --> 00:16:55,500
I just want to concur with Representative McGee.

128
00:16:55,500 --> 00:17:13,000
I think that going forward with this bill without an analysis would be foolhardy in terms of the economic impact on the state and the businesses that are already involved in the clean energy transition.

129
00:17:13,000 --> 00:17:36,000
But I also think that we need to look at the purpose of the RPS, which is to bring on more clean energy in order to transition us away from our dependence on fossil fuels because of the impact of burning fossil fuels on the climate.

130
00:17:36,000 --> 00:17:38,500
That's a very real thing.

131
00:17:38,500 --> 00:17:55,500
And to question that is, you know, is to deny the science, the consensus on the need to do that in order to, you know, save us from the worst impacts of climate change.

132
00:17:55,500 --> 00:17:59,000
So I just wanted to mention that.

133
00:17:59,000 --> 00:18:01,000
Okay.

134
00:18:01,000 --> 00:18:03,000
Additional comments?

135
00:18:03,000 --> 00:18:05,000
Representative Reynolds.

136
00:18:05,000 --> 00:18:07,000
Thank you, Mr.

137
00:18:07,000 --> 00:18:09,000
Chairman.

138
00:18:09,000 --> 00:18:17,000
Just want to chime in and support my ranking member and my fellow member, Representative Kaplan.

139
00:18:17,000 --> 00:18:21,000
The Renewable Portfolio Standard is longstanding public policy.

140
00:18:21,000 --> 00:18:29,500
New Hampshire's one of something like 34, 35, two-thirds of states in the United States have one.

141
00:18:29,500 --> 00:18:35,000
It's public policy, prudent policy to diversify this state's energy resources.

142
00:18:35,000 --> 00:18:38,500
New Hampshire has no native fossil fuels.

143
00:18:38,500 --> 00:18:43,500
The only native energy sources we have are renewable sources.

144
00:18:43,500 --> 00:18:55,500
And so we should do nothing to reduce incentives and support for further development of renewable energy resources because they strengthen the state economically.

145
00:18:55,500 --> 00:19:00,500
So I also would not support moving this bill forward.

146
00:19:00,500 --> 00:19:03,500
Representative McWilliams, nice to see you.

147
00:19:03,500 --> 00:19:06,500
Good to see you as well.

148
00:19:06,500 --> 00:19:08,500
Thank you, Chair Boz.

149
00:19:08,500 --> 00:19:26,500
I just wanted to make a quick comment that we have existing biomass facilities that are both county and state-owned that would be impacted by the removal of the RPS because of their biomass right now.

150
00:19:26,500 --> 00:19:39,500
That is a business impact on what we're concerned about, big picture, federal, state, and local county-owned facilities that right now are benefiting from the RPS.

151
00:19:39,500 --> 00:19:52,500
And we really should look at that, I think, in a little bit more granularity before just pulling the rug out from underneath those business cases.

152
00:19:52,500 --> 00:19:54,500
Thank you.

153
00:19:54,500 --> 00:19:56,500
Representative Harrington.

154
00:19:56,500 --> 00:20:01,000
Yeah, just a couple of quick replies to that.

155
00:20:01,000 --> 00:20:11,500
First, obviously, any company that's getting a subsidy from ratepayers or taxpayers is going to complain when the subsidy goes away.

156
00:20:11,500 --> 00:20:15,000
That doesn't mean it should be perpetual.

157
00:20:15,000 --> 00:20:29,000
This was set with an end limit to allow renewable energy to grow and to educate the people on the need for that, both of which have happened.

158
00:20:29,000 --> 00:20:31,000
Thank you.

159
00:20:31,000 --> 00:20:33,000
it should be perpetual.

160
00:20:33,000 --> 00:20:47,000
This was set with an end limit to allow renewable energy to grow and to educate the people on the need for that, both of which have happened.

161
00:20:47,000 --> 00:20:51,500
We cannot just go on forever with the subsidies.

162
00:20:51,500 --> 00:20:57,000
It's response to what counties may have something of doing this.

163
00:20:57,000 --> 00:21:06,000
Well, the people in my county shouldn't have to pay higher electric rates to subsidize some other county.

164
00:21:06,000 --> 00:21:08,500
It's simply not their responsibility.

165
00:21:08,500 --> 00:21:12,500
Let the county pay for their own cost.

166
00:21:12,500 --> 00:21:24,000
The other part about this is we talk about, you know, our renewable energy in the state, we don't have any fossil fuels.

167
00:21:24,000 --> 00:21:39,500
Well, the switch from coal and oil to natural gas accounted for almost 95% of the reduction in carbon dioxide emissions in New England over the last 10 or 15 years.

168
00:21:39,500 --> 00:21:59,500
So using natural gas is a much cleaner source that we should be looking at making that happen with more pipelines or at least getting rid of the Jones Act so we can get an LNG from the United States.

169
00:21:59,500 --> 00:22:38,500
But the renewable energy source we want to look at, as Luke mentioned, wood, well, we just, there was a settlement just made, maybe you're aware of this, but the biomass plant in Berlin went bankrupt because they could not get another, I think it would have been their third extension for not having to live up to the terms of the contract that they not only signed, but they pursued with Eversource that was public service then.

170
00:22:38,500 --> 00:22:43,000
Now, that bankruptcy left the ratepayers owed $160 million.

171
00:22:43,000 --> 00:22:52,500
So this is what happens when the government gets involved in the markets and tries to artificially set prices.

172
00:22:52,500 --> 00:23:02,000
It's $160 million that the ratepayers paid to that biomass facility that they're never going to see back again.

173
00:23:02,000 --> 00:23:12,500
And you might also know, how did they use some of that $160 million that they were paid over market rates?

174
00:23:12,500 --> 00:23:20,000
They hired very expensive lobbyists to come down here to lobby for more ratepayer subsidies.

175
00:23:20,000 --> 00:23:29,500
So basically, that bill forced the ratepayers to pay for people to raise the subsidies that they were paying.

176
00:23:29,500 --> 00:23:34,000
That's what happens when the government interferes with markets.

177
00:23:34,000 --> 00:23:37,500
We had a plan, ended in 2025.

178
00:23:37,500 --> 00:23:40,000
Everybody knows about renewable energy.

179
00:23:40,000 --> 00:23:45,500
Anyone can go out and buy it if they want to.

180
00:23:45,500 --> 00:23:49,500
There's nothing that stops them from doing it.

181
00:23:49,500 --> 00:23:51,500
It's available.

182
00:23:51,500 --> 00:23:55,500
Just look on the internet under the PUC.

183
00:23:55,500 --> 00:24:00,000
There's simply no need to extend this subsidy forever.

184
00:24:00,000 --> 00:24:02,000
Who's next?

185
00:24:02,000 --> 00:24:04,000
Representative Korman.

186
00:24:04,000 --> 00:24:06,000
Thank you, Mr.

187
00:24:06,000 --> 00:24:08,000
Chairman.

188
00:24:08,000 --> 00:24:21,500
Representative Reynolds said something that I was thinking at that moment, which is actually harking back to something that you had been pointing out and advocating, Mr.

189
00:24:21,500 --> 00:24:25,000
Chairman, and that's New Hampshire energy independence.

190
00:24:25,000 --> 00:24:28,500
And we don't produce the fossil fuels.

191
00:24:28,500 --> 00:24:32,000
We don't produce coal, oil, natural gas.

192
00:24:32,000 --> 00:24:43,500
If we are going to move toward energy independence, it's going to have to be with renewable energy that we produce in state.

193
00:24:43,500 --> 00:24:47,500
So I think we should be supporting it.

194
00:24:47,500 --> 00:24:51,500
Another possibility there might be small modular nuclear.

195
00:24:51,500 --> 00:24:55,500
So that's something we should keep in mind.

196
00:24:55,500 --> 00:24:58,500
We get regular reports every year.

197
00:24:58,500 --> 00:25:11,500
I'm sure every member of this committee gets them in their email inbox from the Department of Energy tracking the previous year's implementation of the RPS.

198
00:25:11,500 --> 00:25:15,000
So we know how much it costs.

199
00:25:15,000 --> 00:25:19,000
And we also, individually, I'm sure, get completed.

200
00:25:19,000 --> 00:25:23,000
tracking the previous year's implementation of the RPS.

201
00:25:23,000 --> 00:25:26,500
So we know how much it costs.

202
00:25:26,500 --> 00:25:34,500
And we also individually, I'm sure, get complaints from constituents about the high cost of electricity.

203
00:25:34,500 --> 00:25:45,000
And the RPS, according to the reports we get every year, costs ratepayers something like $55 million, $60 million every year.

204
00:25:45,000 --> 00:25:57,000
And phasing out the RPS would be something that I think ratepayers would be in favor of because it would lower their electric costs.

205
00:25:57,000 --> 00:26:01,500
So that's something to keep in mind as well.

