1045
01:54:25,000 --> 01:54:34,000
They were correct because the site evaluation committee does not look at cost, does not look at need.

1046
01:54:34,000 --> 01:54:55,000
The idea is if somebody wants to build a whatever 40 megawatt power plant, the question is, does it comply with all of New Hampshire's siting laws, not whether the power plant is necessary or if it's expensive or not too inexpensive.

1047
01:54:55,000 --> 01:55:07,500
The problem with the transmission is, as my friend from Rhode Island coined the phrase, transmission is the largest unregulated monopoly in the United States.

1048
01:55:07,500 --> 01:55:24,500
And I checked with Nesco on this, New England States Committee on Electricity, or the New England, whatever it is, New England States Committee on Electricity, and that represents all six of the states.

1049
01:55:24,500 --> 01:55:41,000
They've put this as their number one issue and their report to all six New England, whatever it is, New England State's Community on Electricity, and that represents all six of the states.

1050
01:55:41,000 --> 01:56:00,500
They've put this as their number one issue to the, and their report to all six New England governors for this year, saying that this was going to be billions of dollars and it's not looked at by anybody.

1051
01:56:00,500 --> 01:56:19,000
According to the people at Nesco, they even checked with FERC, who would have jurisdiction over transmission, and they were told, if you send something down to us, we don't have anyone to look at it anyways.

1052
01:56:19,000 --> 01:56:23,500
So basically, there is no one looking at this.

1053
01:56:23,500 --> 01:56:32,000
And as much as I believe in free markets, this isn't a free market, it's a monopoly.

1054
01:56:32,000 --> 01:56:37,000
So if it's a monopoly, it needs to be regulated.

1055
01:56:37,000 --> 01:56:42,500
And we have to look at a way of doing that.

1056
01:56:42,500 --> 01:57:11,000
