1104
02:04:29,000 --> 02:04:40,500
So our commission has been, this is the third iteration of this commission, and we have been studying a solution to this problem.

1105
02:04:40,500 --> 02:04:52,000
And I'm relatively certain, although we still have three or four more meetings before we generate a report, we've already had four meetings.

1106
02:04:52,000 --> 02:05:01,000
But I'm relatively certain that we're going to submit legislation to remove generation from the utility property tax.

1107
02:05:01,000 --> 02:05:05,500
And that will remove the DRA from the equation.

1108
02:05:05,500 --> 02:05:13,000
So the only assessing of power plants will be done by assessors hired by municipalities.

1109
02:05:13,000 --> 02:05:20,500
So removing that contention between these two different evaluations should significantly reduce lawsuits and litigation.

1110
02:05:20,500 --> 02:05:25,000
It won't completely eliminate it, but it'll reduce it.

1111
02:05:25,000 --> 02:05:38,500
The points of contention that we're wrestling with right now is whether we should require the utilities to do some kind of reporting on their business income.

1112
02:05:38,500 --> 02:05:42,000
We don't require that of other manufacturers.

1113
02:05:42,000 --> 02:06:00,000
And if you consider a utility to be a manufacturer of electricity, then the question is, should we require them to report on the value of what they produce and use that in the assessing process?

1114
02:06:00,000 --> 02:06:06,500
That currently happens, but the generators say that it shouldn't happen going forward.

1115
02:06:06,500 --> 02:06:20,000
The other issue we're wrestling with a little bit is equalization, because a generation plant, unlike a house, doesn't change value up and down like houses do.

1116
02:06:20,000 --> 02:06:24,000
Its value is pretty steady throughout its lifetime.

1117
02:06:24,000 --> 02:06:43,000
